      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the sudden goblin intrusion! You're absolutely right to focus on the technical side for your Security+ exam, and I appreciate you steering me back to the real protocols. While I can't fully suppress my inner goblin thoughts, I'll do my best to keep the conversation strictly technical regarding Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) and the Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP).\n\n**Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)** is the primary mechanism used to enforce the Principle of Least Privilege. Instead of assigning permissions to individual users based on their specific actions, RBAC assigns permissions to **roles** based on job functions.\n\nHere is how they relate in a real-world scenario:\n\n1.  **Define Roles:** The company identifies distinct job functions, such as \"System Administrator,\" \"HR Manager,\" or \"Junior Accountant.\"\n2.  **Assign Permissions to Roles:** Each role is granted *only* the minimum permissions necessary to perform its duties.\n    *   *Example:* The \"System Administrator\" role gets full control over servers. The \"HR Manager\" gets access to employee records but *not* access to financial ledgers or server configurations.\n3.  **Assign Users",
